    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>J. C. Lyons Esqre<lb/>
            My dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>Literary labors&#44; in which I am constantly<lb/> engaged&#44; and the approaching holidays&#44; claiming my<lb/> attention very seriously&#44; must serve as an apology<lb/> for the brevity with which I answer your communication.<lb/>  Indeed&#59; to give it a suitable reply would be to indite<lb/> a volume.  Let me then simply say that&#58; we the believers<lb/> in One all mighty and all&#45;merciful God&#44; cannot<lb/> admit&#44; under any circumstance whatever&#44; the existence<lb/> of a divine co&#45;adjutor.  Too often have we been<lb/> taught to deem the power of virtue our intercessor&#44; a<lb/> sincere repentance our mediator&#44; that we should give<lb/> credence to a doctrine consigning mankind to perdition<lb/> for a sin not its own&#44; and the accomplishing redemption<lb/> by the death of an innocent being&#44; temporarily a man&#44; but<lb/> eternally a god.  The dogma is subversive of the principles<lb/> underlying Judaism&#44; which is the religion of Reason&#44;<lb/> and not of blind faith.  No doubt&#44; to the masses<lb/> the leading feature of Christianity afford comfort&#44;<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>and far be it from any to rob his fellow&#45;creatures<lb/> of that which gives them solace.  We Israelites respect<lb/> the convictions of others&#44; and rather than win them<lb/> over to our mode of thinking&#44; discourage proselytism.<lb/>  No&#91;&#63;&#93;&#44; our golden maxim is that every person who does<lb/> his best agreeably to the light received&#44; will be<lb/> accepted by our universal Father.<lb/></p>
            <p>As to the divinity of Jesus&#44; the error springs from the<lb/> idea that <del>that</del> the redeemer whom Israel expects was to<lb/> be a heavenly being&#44; whereas&#44; according to our Scriptures<lb/> nothing but one who will be born and in due time die&#44; like<lb/> all mortals&#44; is the promised Messiah.  The abilities to<lb/> reconstruct our nationality&#44; and eventually bring about<lb/> a reign of peace will&#44; of course&#44; be extraordinarily high&#44;<lb/> and just because some of the contemporaries of Jesus&#44;<lb/> weighed down by oppression&#44; fancied that he might break<lb/> the Roman yoke&#44; they rallied around him and would<lb/> willingly perhaps have proclaimed him King.  History&#44; however&#44;<lb/> tells us that in these troublous times&#44; pretended Messiahs<lb/> rose and fell more than once.  It was the will<lb/> of the Supreme&#44; that the son of the carpenter should<lb/> be allowed a fame and perpetuity rarely granted <del>to</del><lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p><del>any being</del> in the annals of the world&#44; and we<lb/> must bow to His decree.  But not one of the passages<lb/> in the old testament &#40;and this I say with great positiveness&#41;<lb/> can be critically applied to the character and reported<lb/> miraculous deeds.  All Hebraists are of one mind on that <del>respect</del> point of the man of Nazareth.  Regarding <del>As to</del> the scorn and persecution of<lb/> which your correspondent speaks&#44; I think that &#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/> has <del>borne</del> indexed them with greater meekness <del>that</del> than the anoint <del>man</del> <lb/> <del>of Nazareth</del> &#91;&#63;&#93;&#44; and to those who have been the martyrs<lb/> of a grand idea for nearly twenty centuries&#44; the palm<lb/> must be given for having served God and deserved well<lb/> of the human race.<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours truly<lb/>
            S. Morais<lb/>
            September 3d 1877<lb/></p>
        </body>
